Definition: Any living organism characterized by voluntary movement, the possession of cells with noncellulose cell walls and specialized sense organs enabling rapid response to stimuli, and the ingestion of complex organic substances such as plants and other animals.
Any of the bipedal, warm-blooded vertebrates that lay eggs having wings which, for most species, enables them to fly.
A common four-legged animal, especially kept by people as a pet or to hunt or guard things.
A large wild canid (Canidae), closely related to the dog.
Refers to *genus canis*, a genus containing seven to ten extant species, including wolves, domestic dogs, coyotes, and jackals.
A common four-legged animal (Felis silvestris) that is often kept as a household pet.
Of, relating to, or denoting the sex which is generally characterized as the one associated with the larger gametes (for species which have two sexes and for which this distinction can be made).
Of, relating to, or denoting a member of the sex that begets young by fertilizing ova.
A flying stinging insect related to the bee, which is usually coloured yellow and black.
A joint formed where the foot and the leg meet.
The lower opening of the digestive tract, through which faeces pass.
Extremities emerging from the upper part of the human body.
The upper limb, extending from the shoulder to the wrist and sometimes including the hand.
The hollow under the upper part of the arm at the shoulder.
A blood vessel transporting blood away from the heart.
The back part of the head.
The rear of body, especially the part between the neck and the end of the spine and opposite the chest and belly.
Without hair on the head.
Facial hair of humans on the chin, cheeks and jaw.
A pale yellowish-brown color usually of hair.
The blood vessels are the part of the circulatory system that transports blood throughout the human body or an animal body.
A fluid connective tissue consisting of the plasma and cells that circulate in the blood vessels.
The terminal hair that develops on the human body during and after puberty.
Part of a human body or an animal body.
The physical structure of a human or animal.
A painful, local inflammation of the skin, caused by infection of a hair follicle. Usually, a hard core and pus are present.
Any of the components of an endoskeleton, consisting mainly of calcium phosphate, collagen and cells.
The organ of the central nervous system of an animal or human located in the skull that controls the actions and thoughts of the animal or human.
The milk of humans.
The fleshy organ on the chest of a sexually mature human female containing mammary glands.
The air inhaled and exhaled through the lungs.
To repeatedly draw air into, and expel it from, the lungs, in order to extract oxygen from it and excrete waste products.
A collection of blood in the body tissue outside the blood vessels
To release gas from the digestive tract through the mouth.
The fleshy part of the human body that one sits on.
The body of a dead animal, on which other animals have begun to feed.
The soft skin on each side of the face, between the eyes and the chin; the outer surface of the sides of the oral cavity.
The portion of the body from the base of the neck to the top of the abdomen; the thorax.
The bottom of the face, below the mouth.
A part of the female genitalia located at the front of the vulva, consisting of a sensitive erectile body.
A dead body.
The organ that is sensitive to light, which it converts to electrical signals passed to the brain, by which means animals and humans see.
The partly visible orb nesting in the eye socket which contains for example pupil, retina and iris and is connected to the brain via the optic nerve.
The hair that grows over the bone ridge above the eye socket.
One of the hairs that grows on the eyelid, around the eyes.
A skin flap that can be closed over an eye.
The front part of the head, featuring the eyes, nose, and mouth and the surrounding area.
A branching, hair-like structure that grows on the skin of birds and protects them against coldness and water and allows their wings to create lift.
Limb of the human body found in the hands and foots of humans and primates.
One of the long extremities of the hand that is used for gripping objects.
The hard, flat, translucent covering near the tip of a human finger, useful for scratching and fine manipulation.
The top of the finger.
Any of the bones forming the skeleton of a fish, especially one of the sharp slender bones attached to the backbone.
The closed hand with the fingers on the palm.
Lower part of the human body which is used for walking.
The part of a humanâ€™s body below the ankle that is used in order to stand and walk.
The finger between thumb and long finger.
The part of the face between the hairline and the eyebrows.
The body-hair of an animal (excluding humans) or a piece of clothing made thereof.
The sexual organs: the testicles and penis of a male; or the labia, clitoris, and vagina of a female.
The mucosal tissue that partly lies over the teeth in the mouth.
That part of the fore limb below the forearm or wrist in primates (including humans).
The hair on the head of humans (rather than the hair in general or the hair on the body).
The part of the body of an animal or human which contains the brain, mouth and main sense organs.
A muscular organ that pumps blood through the body.
The hair on humans, usually on the head but also including the hair on the body.
The outer tissue of human beings.
Either of the two opposable structures forming, or near the entrance to, the mouth.
Any part of the body where two bones join.
An organ in the body that produces urine.
In man, the joint in the middle part of the leg.
Joints of the fingers brought to prominence when hand is clenched.
Organ on the upper end of the trachea.
The limb of an animal (including humans) that extends from the groin to the ankle.
The part of the body (of humans and quadrupeds) each side of the backbone between the ribs and hips.
The part of the arm between the elbow and the hand.
The lower part of the spine, also known as the lumbar region, which is situated between the rib cage and the pelvis.
Part of the leg between the knee and the foot.
The lower fleshy protrusion around the opening of the mouth.
A biological organ that extracts oxygen from the air.
The long hair in the neck of horses and lions.
A growth of facial hair between the nose and the upper lip.
Opening in the lower half of a human face which is used for food ingestion and articulation.
An organ formed by contractile tissue that moves other organs.
Hard keratin part growing at the end of a human's finger or toe.
The back part of the neck.
Mucus from the nose.
A scar where the umbilical cord was attached.
The part of the body (found in some animals, including humans) that connects the head and the trunk.
An enclosed, cable-like bundle of axons (nerve fibers, the long and slender projections of neurons) in the peripheral nervous system.
The projection of a mammary gland from which, on female mammals, milk can be secreted.
The organ of the face used to breath and smell.
Either of the two orifices located on the nose (or on the beak of a bird); used as a passage for air and other gases to travel the nasal passages.
Cavity that is limited by the lips in front, the cheeks on the side, the soft and hard palate at the top and the floor of the mouth below.
The female sex organ which is often paired and produces eggs for procreation.
The palate is the roof of the mouth in humans and other mammals.
The inner and somewhat concave part of the human hand that extends from the wrist to the bases of the fingers.
An organ of the digestive system of vertebrates.
The male sexual organ for copulation and urination; the tubular portion of the male genitalia (excluding the scrotum).
The inner part of the neck which starts after the oral and nasal cavity.
Dense, coarse hair that grows on the male and female genital area beginning in puberty.
Contractile aperture in iris.
One of the long curved bones which form the rib cage.
A secretion from the salivary glands (found in the mouth) that can be spat out.
A permanent mark on the skin resulting from a wound.
Anatomical male reproductive structure.
An organic fluid that may contain spermatozoa. It is secreted by the gonads (sexual glands) and other sexual organs of male or hermaphroditic animals and can fertilize female ova.
One side of the top of the torso, where an arm attaches or joins.
A large flat bone located at the back of each shoulder.
The side of the body.
The body part that forms the supporting structure inside of the human body or the body of animals.

The tissue forming the outer covering of the vertebrate body: it consists of two layers, the outermost of which may be covered with hair, scales, feathers, etc. It is mainly protective and sensory in function.
The main bone of the head; the cranium.
The bottom of the foot.
Men's semen.
The body part that consists of a row of vertebrae, that support the head and torso and that forms a canal for nerves.
To forcefully evacuate saliva from the mouth.
A ductless vascular gland, located in the left upper abdomen near the stomach.
The appendage of an animal that is attached to its posterior and near the anus.
Tissue that connects muscle to bone.
The male sex gland that produces sperm and male hormones, found in some types of animals and humans.
The area between the pelvis and buttocks and the knee.
The front part of the neck.
The shortest and thickest of the fingers that can be placed against the others in order to create a firm grip.
One of the extremities of the foot.
The hard keratin substance covering the tips of the feet of human beings.

The flexible muscular organ in the mouth that is used to move food around, for tasting and that is moved into various positions to modify the flow of air from the lungs in order to produce different sounds.
A hard, calcareous structure present in the mouth of many vertebrate animals (including humans), generally used for eating.
The central part of the human body, from which neck and limbs extend.
An organ in female quadruped mammals which consists of mammary glands and has several teats.
An open sore of the skin, eyes or mucous membrane, often caused by an initial abrasion and generally maintained by an inflammation and/or an infection.
A conduit between the developing embryo or fetus and the placenta.
The part of the arm between the shoulder and the elbow.
The upper part of the back.
The part of the leg between the pelvis and the knee.
Liquid excrement consisting of water, salts and urea, which is made in the kidneys, stored in the bladder, then released through the urethra.
A conic projection from the posterior edge of the middle of the soft palate.
The lower part of the female reproductive tract; a moist canal in female mammals (including humans) extending from the labia minora to the uterus.
A blood vessel that transports blood from the capillaries back to the heart.
The external parts of the female genitalia, in human beings this consists of the labia, clitoris, opening of the urethra (meatus), and the opening of the vagina.
In human beings, the part between the thorax and hips.
Typically small, rough, and hard growths that are similar in color to the rest of the skin.
The appendage of an animal's (bird, bat, insect) body that enables it to fly in the air.
The major female reproductive organ of most mammals, including humans. It is a large muscle enveloping the phoetus during pregnancy.
A type of injury in which in skin or tisue is torn, cut,  punctured or otherwise hurt.
A fold, ridge or crease in the skin.
The flexible and narrower connection between the forearm and the hand.
The galaxy that contains our Solar System. Its name milky is derived from its appearance as a dim glowing band arching across the night sky in which the naked eye cannot distinguish individual stars.
A natural satellite of a planet.
A constellation of stars visible from around the world.
A pattern of three stars in the constellation Orion.
Referring to Polaris or Alpha Ursae Minoris, a star aligned with earthâ€™s axis of rotation and often used for navigation.
A luminous celestial body that is made from gases (particularly hydrogen and helium) and forms the shape of a sphere.
The particular star at the centre of our solar system, from which the Earth gets light and heat.
A large group of stars in the shape of a bear visible on the northern hemisphere.
A very ductile malleable brilliant greyish-white element with symbol Ar and atomic number 47 having the highest electrical and thermal conductivity of any metal.
A metallic chemical element of silver-white colour that occurs mainly in bauxite, with assigned symbol Al and proton number 13.
A heavy yellow elemental metal of great value, with atomic number 79 and symbol Au.

Chemical element with symbol Cu and atomic number 29; one of the most important nonferrous metals; a ductile and malleable metal found in various ores and used in industry, engineering, and the arts in both pure and alloyed form.

A malleable ductile silvery-white ferromagnetic metallic element with symbol Fe and atomic number 26, occurring principally in haematite and magnetite. It is widely used for structural and engineering purposes.

A heavy toxic bluish-white metallic element with symbol Pb and atomic number 82 that is highly malleable; occurs principally as galena and is used in alloys, accumulators, cable sheaths, paints, and as a radiation shield.
A crystalline solid, nonmetallic chemical element of a distinct yellow colour, with assigned symbol S and proton number 16.
A metallic element with symbol Sn, occurring in cassiterite. It is a malleable silvery-white metal.
Person from whom a person is descended, whether on the father's or mother's side, at any number of generations.
A woman with one or more siblings who have one or more children; a sister of someone's father or mother.
A woman who is going to get married or has just got married.
The brother of a man.
The brother of a woman.
The brother of one's partner in a marriage.
A male person who has the same parents as another person.
The spouse of someone's child.
A young human or the descendant of a human.
The child of the sibling of a parent of a person.
An animal's female offspring (including that of a human).
Legal dissolution of a marriage.
To end one's marriage by a legal process.
A group comprising parents, offsprings and others closely related or associated with them.
A male parent.

A daughter of someone's child.
The father of one of someone's parents.
The mother of one of someone's parents.

A man who is going to get married or has just married.
The male partner in a marriage.
To force someone to get married, usually a relative.
To enter marriage; to take a husband or a wife.
A woman who has at least one child.
A person one or both of whose parents have died, especially a minor.
Father and mother of a child.
A person who has the same parents as another person.
A female person who has the same parents as another person.
The male marital partner of someone's child.
One's male child.
One of the partners in a marriage, be they male or female.
The child of one's spouse and his or her previous partner.
The daughter of one's spouse and his or her previous partner.
The husband of one's biological mother, other than one's biological father.
The wife of one's biological father, other than one's biological mother.
The son of one's spouse and his or her previous partner.

A woman whose spouse has died.
A man whose spouse has died.
The female partner in a marriage.
The flower of the Apricot Tree.
The flower of the Chinese Plum.
A drink (a liquor or brew) containing ethanol, commonly known as alcohol.
To cook (something) in an oven, but not in fat.
A fermented drink is a beverage containing alcohol because of a metabolic process that converts sugar to acids, gases and/or alcohol (e.g. beer or wine).
The popular, crisp, round fruit of the apple tree, usually with red, yellow or green skin, light-coloured flesh and pips inside.
The fruit of the banana tree.
A kind of banana that is normally cooked and not eaten raw.
A fruit of orange color with a fuzzy peel and a black seed inside, similar to a peach or plum of a tree from the family Prunus armeniaca.
A small dish for placing a cup.
A length of intestine, stuffed with ground (organ) meat, and other ingredients. Instead of intestines, a different kind of wrapper can be used.
A fully grown and mature person.
A very young human being, from birth to a year old.
A person with an evil character.
A child born of parents not married to each other.
Term used to describe men who are perceived to be dark-skinned.
Term used to describe women who are perceived to be dark-skinned.
Person who has a complete lack of form and visual light perception.
Either a son or a boy.

A person with a brave character.
A person below the age of puberty.
Either a daughter or a girl.
Person who is  partial or total unable to hear.
Relating to the female sex of humans.

Relating to the male sex of humans.
Either a man or a person (in general).
An adult human member of the sex that begets young by fertilizing ova.
A male person who is old of age.
An older person (usually considered to be above the age of 60).
An old woman.
Either multiple human beings or one human being.
A human being.
A person who has never engaged in sexual intercourse.
Term used to describe men who are perceived to be light-skinned.
Term used to describe women who are perceived to be light-skinned.

A male juvenile between the onset of puberty and maturity; in the state of development between puberty and maturity.
A female juvenile between the onset of puberty and maturity; in the state of development between puberty and maturity.
A musical instrument.
A simple sound-making device.
Any musical instrument that is a member of the brass family of musical instruments, usually a horn or a trumpet.
To lead some kind of musical performance.
A series of rhythmic movements performed to music.
To move with rhythmic steps or movements, especially in time to music.
A percussion instrument consisting of at least one membrane that is stretched over a shell and struck directly with the player's hands or with a drumstick.
A two-stringed fiddle common in Eastern Asia; Chinese violin, Chinese two-stringed fiddle.
A musical instrument of the woodwind family.
A traditional piece of music with words to sing.
An African, East and South East Asian musical percussion instrument that takes the form of a flat, circular metal disc which is hit with a mallet.
Musical instrument with usually six strings.
A mouth organ (musical instrument).
A string musical instrument.
A wind instrument made of a wound copper tube with a wide sound bucket and valves.
One of a cluster of small bells, shaken or tapped on the palm of the player's hand. The small metal discs arranged around the frame of a tambourine are also called "jingles".
A plucked string musical instrument with with a neck and a deep round back.
Lamellophone instrument consisting of a tongue or reed attached to a frame, placed in the performer's mouth and plucked; Jew's harp, jaw harp.

A large musical instrument with a row of black and white keys that are pressed to play notes.

To produce harmonious sounds with one's voice.
A musical piece with lyrics (or words to sing); prose that one can sing.
Musical instrument with round, wooden frame and covered by skin, plastic, etc. with metal discs around the frame.

A musical instrument in the brass family.
Wind instrument most often made out of metal or wood used for producing a loud, shrill tone.
A tropical plant with edible multiple fruit consisting of coalesced berries, also called pineapples, and the most economically significant plant in the Bromeliaceae family.
A tree of the genus Betula, with small leaves and a trunk that is white with darker blotches.
A bud is an undeveloped or embryonic shoot and normally occurs in the axil of a leaf or at the tip of the stem.
The tropical treelike plant which bears clusters of bananas. The plant, of the genus Musa, has large, elongated leaves.
One of two main structural axes of a vascular plant, the other being the root.

Any living organism that synthesizes its food from inorganic substances, possesses cellulose cell walls, responds slowly and often permanently to a stimulus, lacks specialized sense organs and nervous system, and has no powers of locomotion.
A tree that bears the apricot fruit.
An Asian tree species classified in the Armeniaca section of the genus Prunus subgenus Prunus.

To ring the bells.
To utter the characteristic cry of a rooster.
Reflection of sound.
To perceive sound with the ear, with or without paying attention to it.
To perceive sound with the ear, without necessarily paying attention to it.
To perceive with the ear (paying attention to what is heard).
(Of a sound) to have a high volume.
Sound which is unwanted, either because of its effects on humans, its effect on fatigue or malfunction of physical equipment, or its interference with the perception or detection of other sounds.
With little or no sound; denoting absence of disturbing noise.
Ring most broadly refers to a hollow circular shape or to a high-pitched sound.
Absence of sound, especially of noise.
Any audible noise which is not necessarily unwanted or unpleasant to the hearer and of short or long duration.
The noise emitted by musical instruments or humans speaking.
Emit a sound suggestive of a tinkle.
The amount of time that a person, animal or plant has lived or that an object has existed.
The season after summer and before winter, traditionally from September 21 to December 20 in the northern hemisphere and from March 21 to June 20 in the southern hemisphere.
A period of time lasting 24 hours.
The period between sunrise and sunset where one enjoys daylight.
The future is what will happen in the time after the present.
A time period of sixty minutes; one twenty-fourth of a day.
A period of heavy rain particularly during summer time.
A period into which a year is divided, historically based on the phases of the moon. In the Gregorian calendar there are twelve months.
The period of time from the start of the day (midnight) until midday (12:00).
The period between sunset and sunrise, when a location faces far away from the sun, thus when the sky is dark.
On the current day or in the current moment.
At present; at this time.
Many times, with short intervals between occasions.
Having lived or existed for a relatively long period of time.
An instance or occurrence of an event.

One of the four equal periods into which the year is divided by the equinoxes and solstices, resulting from the apparent movement of the sun north and south of the equator during the course of the earth's orbit around it. These periods (spring, summer, autumn and winter) have their characteristic weather conditions in different regions, and occur at opposite times of the year in the N and S hemispheres.
Traditionally the first of the four seasons, the season of growth with an ever increasing amount of daytime.

Traditionally the second of the four seasons regarded as being from June 21 to September 20 (or just June, July and August) in the Northern Hemisphere and from December 21 to March 20 (or just December, January and February) in the Southern Hemisphere.
A period of seven days.

Traditionally, the fourth of the seasons, marked by the applicable hemisphere of the planet being at its minimum angle of exposure to the Sun, resulting in short days, long nights and typically in low temperatures.
The time it takes the Earth to complete one revolution of the Sun (between 365.24 and 365.26 days depending on the point of reference).
